{"id":"2208.10604","submitter":"Atticus Stonestrom","authors":"Atticus Stonestrom","title":"Product-free sets in approximate subgroups of distal groups","comments":"added some remarks on the case G=GLn(C), an appendix on solvable\n  groups, and some more references","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO math.LO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  Recall that a subset $X$ of a group $G$ is 'product-free' if $X^2\\cap\nX=\\varnothing$, ie if $xy\\notin X$ for all $x,y\\in X$. Let $G$ be a group\ndefinable in a distal structure. We prove there are constants $c>0$ and\n$\\delta\\in(0,1)$ such that every finite subset $X\\subseteq G$ distinct from\n$\\{1\\}$ contains a product-free subset of size at least\n$\\delta|X|^{c+1}/|X^2|^c$. In particular, every finite $k$-approximate subgroup\nof $G$ distinct from $\\{1\\}$ contains a product-free subset of density at least\n$\\delta/k^c$. The proof is short, and follows quickly from Ruzsa calculus and\nan iterated application of Chernikov and Starchenko's distal regularity lemma.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 22 Aug 2022 21:22:42 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 29 Aug 2022 16:54:33 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Wed, 19 Apr 2023 16:54:51 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-20"}
